(56775, 1951, 56749, 'Malik1', 78, '', 1254230709, 'a.	[u][b]Parallax[/b][/u].	Parallax is an apparent displacement or difference of orientation of an object viewed along two different lines of sight, and is measured by the angle or semi-angle of inclination between those two lines. The term is derived from the Greek ?????????? (parallaxis), meaning "alteration". Nearby objects have a larger parallax than more distant objects when observed from different positions, so parallax can be used to determine distances. Parallax also affects optical instruments such as binoculars, microscopes, and twin-lens reflex cameras that view objects from slightly different angles. Many animals, including humans, have two eyes with overlapping visual fields to use parallax to gain depth perception; this process is known as stereopsis.', 0, 1, '111.68.99.100', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 2578, 64137),
